Survey of Professional Forecasters Data¶

Column description from SPF:

TLDR:

  • 1 - prior quarter
  • 2 - current quarter
  • 3 - 6 - next 4 quarters
  • A - Annual average forecast for current year
  • B - Annual average forecast for next year
  • The forecasts were made in the beginning of the second month of the quarter.

INDPROD description

Forecasts for the quarterly average and annual average level of the index of industrial production. Seasonally adjusted, index, base year varies. Quarterly forecasts are for the quarterly average of the underlying monthly levels. Annual forecasts are for the annual average of the underlying monthly levels.

As you move across a given row, the columns give the forecast for a different quarterly or annual horizon. We distinguish among the horizons by appending “1” to “6” (quarterly forecasts) or “A” and “B” (annual-average forecasts) to a root name identifying the variable forecast. The number “1” represents the “forecast” for the quarter prior to the quarter in which the survey is conducted. The forecasters know the values of the variables for this quarter at the time they submit their projections. For example, for NIPA variables, these values are the Bureau of Economic Analysis’s (BEA) advance estimate for the quarter. The forecasters are permitted to forecast a revision to the BEA’s advance estimate but most do not. Thus, the data in this column correspond closely to the BEA’s advance estimate. The number “2” represents the forecast for the current quarter, defined as the quarter in which the survey is conducted. The numbers “3” through “6” represent the forecasts for the four quarters after the current quarter. The letters “A” and “B” represent annual average forecasts for the current year (the year in which the survey is conducted) and the following year.

Check page 8 in documentation for the timing of Survey of Professional Forecasters. The Deadline for each forecast is the beginning of the second month of the quarter.

# merge actual, trend, and expectation
indproddf2 = pd.merge(indproddf, indprodexpdf.loc[:,['dindprod3']].shift(1)/100., how='left', left_index=True, right_index=True)

# monthly % change in trend annualized
indproddf2['INDPRO Trend'] = np.power((1+indproddf2['INDPRO Trend'].pct_change()),12) - 1

# monthly % change in actual annualized
indproddf2['INDPRO Monthly'] = np.power((1+indproddf2['INDPRO'].pct_change()),12) - 1

# fill in quarterly expectations which are already annualized
indproddf2['dindprod3'] = indproddf2['dindprod3'].fillna(method='bfill',limit=2)

# quarterly series
indproddf2['INDPRO Quarterly'] = indproddf2['INDPRO'].resample('Q').last()
# quarterly % change
indproddf2['INDPRO Quarterly'] = indproddf2['INDPRO Quarterly'].dropna().pct_change()
# fill in each month
indproddf2['INDPRO Quarterly'] = indproddf2['INDPRO Quarterly'].fillna(method='bfill',limit=2)
# annualize
indproddf2['INDPRO Quarterly'] = np.power(1+indproddf2['INDPRO Quarterly'],4) - 1

I decided to normalize by only dividing by sample standard deviation. I did not subtract the mean or the median because that could change a positive surprise to a negative surprise. Practically, I don't think this change much because the mean and the median were both close to 0.

In [10]:
def normalize(series : pd.Series) -> pd.Series:
    return (series)/(series.std(ddof=1))
In [11]:
def create_signal(
    df : pd.DataFrame,
    name_of_expectations_col : str,
    name_of_actual_col : str,
    base_name : str,
    size_of_signal = 0.
) -> pd.DataFrame:
    
    # create surprise index
    df[base_name + ' Surprise'] = df[name_of_expectations_col] - df[name_of_actual_col]
    df[base_name + ' Surprise Normalized'] = normalize(df[base_name + ' Surprise'])
    
    # set signal as true for rising and false for falling
    df[base_name + ' Surprise Signal'] = df[base_name + ' Surprise Normalized'] > size_of_signal
    
    # set nan surprises as nan signals
    nan_mask = pd.isnull(df[base_name + ' Surprise Normalized'])
    df.loc[nan_mask,base_name + ' Surprise Signal'] = np.nan
    
    return df

def combine_signals(
    df : pd.DataFrame,
    signal1_name : str,
    signal2_name : str,
    base_name : str,
    size_of_signal = 0.
) -> pd.DataFrame:
    
    # combine normalized differences
    df[base_name + ' Surprise Normalized'] = (df[signal1_name] + df[signal2_name])/2.
    
    # create combined signal
    df[base_name + ' Surprise Signal'] = df[base_name + ' Surprise Normalized'] > size_of_signal
    
    # set nan surprises as nan signals
    nan_mask = pd.isnull(df[base_name + ' Surprise Normalized'])
    df.loc[nan_mask,base_name + ' Surprise Signal'] = np.nan
    
    return df

             (indproddf2['INDPRO Forecast Surprise Signal'] == False) & 
             (indproddf2['INDPRO Trend Surprise Signal'] == False)
         )*100
     )
)

print("%0.2f%% of time with non overlapping growth signals" % 
     (
         np.mean(
             (
                 (indproddf2['INDPRO Forecast Surprise Signal'] == False) & 
                 (indproddf2['INDPRO Trend Surprise Signal'] == True) 
             ) | (
                 (indproddf2['INDPRO Forecast Surprise Signal'] == True) & 
                 (indproddf2['INDPRO Trend Surprise Signal'] == False)
             )
         )*100
     )
)
print("%0.2f%% of time with nan growth signals" % 
         (
         np.mean(
             pd.isnull(indproddf2['INDPRO Combined Surprise Signal'])
             )*100
         )
)

For the forecast data, we want to use the CPI forecasts but it only goes back to Q3 of 1981. Before Q3 of 1981, I use PGDP which is another price index which goes all the way back to Q4 1968. All credit goes to AQR(https://www.aqr.com/Insights/Research/Journal-Article/Exploring-Macroeconomic-Sensitivities) for solving that problem.

https://www.philadelphiafed.org/research-and-data/real-time-center/survey-of-professional-forecasters/data-files/pgdp

Price Index for Gross National Product/Gross Domestic Product (PGDP) Index level. Seasonally adjusted. GNP deflator prior to 1992. GDP deflator 1992-1995. Chain-weighted price index for GDP 1996-present.

cpidf2 = pd.merge(
    cpidf,
    cpiexpdf.loc[:,['CPI SPF Forecast']].shift(1),
    how='left',
    left_index=True,
    right_index=True
)

# monthly annualized trend changes
cpidf2['CPURNSA Index Trend'] = np.power((1+cpidf2['CPURNSA Index Trend']),12) - 1

# monthly annualized actual changes
cpidf2['CPURNSA Index Monthly'] = np.power((1+cpidf2['CPURNSA Index'].pct_change()),12) - 1

# quarterly annualized actual changes
cpidf2['CPURNSA Index Quarterly'] = cpidf2['CPURNSA Index'].resample('Q').last()
cpidf2['CPURNSA Index Quarterly'] = cpidf2['CPURNSA Index Quarterly'].dropna().pct_change()
cpidf2['CPURNSA Index Quarterly'] = cpidf2['CPURNSA Index Quarterly'].fillna(method='bfill',limit=2)
cpidf2['CPURNSA Index Quarterly'] = np.power(1+cpidf2['CPURNSA Index Quarterly'],4) - 1

         )*100
     )
)

     (
         np.mean(
             (
                 (cpidf2['CPI Forecast Surprise Signal'] == False) & 
                 (cpidf2['CPI Trend Surprise Signal'] == True) 
             ) | (
                 (cpidf2['CPI Forecast Surprise Signal'] == True) & 
                 (cpidf2['CPI Trend Surprise Signal'] == False)
             )
         )*100
     )
)

         (
         np.mean(
             pd.isnull(cpidf2['CPI Combined Surprise Signal'])
             )*100
         )
